    <outline text="art" title="art">
      <outline type="link" text="Christian Marclay on Time, Abstraction and Berlin Nightlife" title="Christian Marclay on Time, Abstraction and Berlin Nightlife" url="https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-clock-christian-marclay-2723438" htmlUrl="https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-clock-christian-marclay-2723438" description="“I’ve always been interested in time and how little time we have,” he said, believing, “we’re all kind of obsessed with time and time stresses us, but time is an abstraction. I think we’re always trying to make it more concrete, but it’s a mental thing. It’s very elastic. And cinema usually plays with that elasticity. Here, I’m setting the clock back on time.”" created="Mon, 05 Jan 2026 12:37:25 GMT" category="time,clock,art,christian-marclay" />
    </outline>
    <outline text="capitalism" title="capitalism">
      <outline type="link" text="Democracy Will Not Survive the Age of Consumption" title="Democracy Will Not Survive the Age of Consumption" url="https://kasurian.com/p/democracy-will-not-survive-consumption" htmlUrl="https://kasurian.com/p/democracy-will-not-survive-consumption" description="In this schema, the productive middle occupies an increasingly untenable position. They are too numerous to ignore but too dispersed to organise effectively. They lack the cultural capital to dominate elite discourse and the electoral weight to dominate mass politics. Their interests are in lower taxes, less regulation, stable money, and predictable institutions; precisely those that the top-bottom coalition has no incentive to provide. What, then, are their options?" created="Sun, 04 Jan 2026 21:47:14 GMT" category="democracy,capitalism" />
      <outline type="link" text="Why Civilizations Flourish—and Fail" title="Why Civilizations Flourish—and Fail" url="https://www.imf.org/en/publications/fandd/issues/2025/12/why-civilizations-flourish-and-fail-johan-norberg" htmlUrl="https://www.imf.org/en/publications/fandd/issues/2025/12/why-civilizations-flourish-and-fail-johan-norberg" description="Often they abandoned the international trade that had brought them wealth and sparked creativity. Sometimes commerce collapsed because wars made roads and sea-lanes unsafe, as in Rome and during the late Renaissance. In a reaction against the openness of Song China, the subsequent Ming dynasty banned foreign trade altogether, and the militarization of the Roman and Abbasid economies extinguished commerce.

Such reactions reduced their ability to adapt locally to changing circumstances. Severed trade routes eroded economic and technological capacity, and new orthodoxies choked off the flow of ideas and solutions that might have helped them manage the crisis. They lost that spirit of curiosity that had once made them great." created="Mon, 05 Jan 2026 13:58:16 GMT" category="capitalism,consumption,trade,global,civilization,open-mindset,history" />
    </outline>
